  "doc_id": "37980",
  "text": "While most problem decomposition techniques examine the correlation relationship between variables, a few algorithms focus on the influence of different decision variables on the convergence and diversity in large-scale multiobjective optimization. García-Sánchez et al. [CITATION_1] extended the distributed coevolutionary island-model [CITATION_2] based on the parallel execution of the subpopulations, whose individuals explore different domains of the decision space. Ma et al. [CITATION_3] proposed a decision variable analysis method based on dominance relationships to divide the decision variables into three groups, i.e., convergence-related variables, diversity-related variables, and variables related to both convergence and diversity. A more effective division method was suggested by Zhang et al. [CITATION_4] using the k-means clustering method with respect to the angles between the solutions and the direction of convergence. As a result, all decision variables are labeled as either convergence-related or diversity-related.",
